This is my out of office in Valencia. ‚ò∫Ô∏è I recently read an article about the use of an OoO in professional practice. For many people setting an out of office response is the final obstacle standing between them and their holiday.

One Chief Exec‚Äôs OoO reads as follows: "I'm off with my family right now. 'll be reading, diving and playing with my boys while they still want to play with me!‚Äù Her argument for including so much detail is to let everyone know that it‚Äôs ok to switch off, by normalising it. 
France has gone even further by giving staff the legal right to "disconnect" and avoid work emails outside working hours.

Meanwhile, an editor-in-chief has written an entire column for The Financial Times on why everyone should say a big fat no to the OoO. He argues they are "out of step with the ways of the modern world" and suggests people who use them simply aren't committed enough.

I completely disagree with him! Clearly he needs a holiday. I think that using an OoO is very much in touch with ‚Äúthe ways of the modern world‚Äù. While I embrace working as a #digitalnomad, sometimes I simply cannot be chained to my desk. I never use an OoO as a standalone mechanism as I always inform my clients that I‚Äôm away from the office with good warning. Any unforeseen email requests will be sent straight to my mobile phone and I‚Äôll be sure to pick them up while I‚Äôm out exploring the world. I‚Äôm very much of the mind that being self-employed provides so much flexibility but it also means that I need to take responsibility for my business and ensure that I always reply promptly to my emails, wherever I am. Even when I‚Äôm on holiday, that‚Äôs not a chore...it‚Äôs just part of my absolute commitment to the career that I love.

What‚Äôs your take on using an OoO? Is it ‚Äúout of step with the ways of the modern world"? üåç
